     3→  "classification": "Moderate",
     4→  "implication": "The patient carries variants of uncertain significance (VUS) in both RYR1 (the primary MH susceptibility gene) and CACNA1S (encoding the DHPR alpha1S subunit, a secondary MH locus). These VUS designations reflect insufficient current evidence to either confirm or exclude malignant hyperthermia susceptibility. RYR1 and CACNA1S encode proteins that physically interact during excitation-contraction coupling; pathogenic variants in either gene can sensitize RyR1-mediated calcium release to volatile anesthetic triggers, potentially causing the life-threatening MH syndrome. Because the functional consequences of these specific uncertain variants on skeletal muscle calcium homeostasis are unknown, the risk of triggering MH with methoxyflurane (a halogenated volatile agent) cannot be reliably quantified. The patient should not be treated as definitively MH-susceptible, but neither can susceptibility be safely excluded."
